Lot's of articles out today about weather and the chance of flying, but it looks like the probabilities for aborting launch remain the same, with 40% chance of abort today and 30% chance of abort on their fallback date. Due to the recent COVID-19 outbreak, SpaceX is unlikely to launch by July. The COVID virus is likely to persist for the next couple of months if not up to a year (https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/how-will-coronavirus-end/608719/). SpaceX and NASA have since delayed launches that were scheduled for late this month (https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/24/spacex-encounters-first-launch-delay-due-to-coronavirus/). However, as of March 18th NASA has invited the media to attend the launch event in May. NASA claims to be monitoring the event but since a week ago, COVID-19 has spread rapidly in the United States, from 4,000 cases on March 16th to 60,000 cases on the 25th. Additionally, Space X itself has been hit by the COVID virus (https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/spacex-one-medical-employees-in-hawthorne-test-positive-for-covid-19.html). In non-COVID related news, the last test before sending humans into space aboard SpaceX rockets encountered a critical engine malfunction during a test (https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/18/spacexs-latest-starlink-launch-included-an-unforeseen-engine-issue/). The failure will require a thorough investigation, which must be completed before the human boarded launch. With external and internal factors piling up, I give this launch a 10% chance of occurring by 1 July 2020.
Due the the COVID-19 virus' rapid spread. I believe that SpaceX will postpone the launch to ensure that the virus has subsided before possibly putting an infected person into space.
Coronavirus will delay the intermediate milestones for testing and the results will likely compound.

Currently, SpaceX is still interested in launching their first crewed mission into orbit. Despite COVD-19 stopping major operations, SpaceX has not made any plans to postpone their mission. It took six years to develop and it is projected to launch in mid to late May. I believe that the world is underestimating COVD-19, especially the United States. With all of the uncertainties, it is very likely that the launch will be postponed to probably in the fall. But, I think the decision to postpone will be very difficult because NASA has been talking about this launch for a very long time. Currently, workers at NASA have been told to work from home and Elon Musk has told workers to not come into work if they are feeling sick, in a way that shows he is downplaying the severity of the virus. The NASA administrator has stated that the agency will keep on moving with important space missions. With all of these uncertainties, it seems that NASA and SpaceX do not know what is the best course of actions, therefore it is likely that the launch will not occur before July. https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/19/21186511/spacex-nasa-crew-dragon-astronauts-launch-may-international-space-station

Space travel is becoming an essential part of the U.S. and global economy as well as an essential part of the private industry. SpaceX is a private company that is investing a lot into space travel and without the presence of the COVID-19 virus, the July 1st deadline for SpaceX to launch the first crewed mission into orbit would be completely feasible. According to a recently published article, SpaceX is taking action to limit the impact of the virus and therefore state that they are confident that their launch schedules would not be impacted. Although the company is confident, there are many uncertainties surrounding the virus, its impact on the economy, and how SpaceX will be impacted by it. However, I chose a percentage that was slightly higher because, as of today, President Trump announced that he would like to have the economy back up and running within two weeks (15-day plan) rather than in months. Because of that, there is now a slightly higher chance (75%) that SpaceX will not be severely impacted by the Coronavirus and therefore may meet its July 1st launch date. https://www.space.com/space-industry-coronavirus-spacex-1st-crewed-launch.html

I want to look at the probability that SpaceX will launch a crewed mission, given the fact that coronavirus has delayed launches as reported by tech crunch (https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/24/spacex-encounters-first-launch-delay-due-to-coronavirus/). According to Bayes' Theorem, the probability of SpaceX failing to launch given the pandemic [P(a/b)] is equal to the probability that the coronavirus will delay a space organization's ability to operate [P(b/a)] times the probability of failing to launch a crewed orbit into space [P(a)] divided by the probability of a non-essential organization being affected by coronavirus [P(b)].

SpaceX just released its timeline for a manned flight to the ISS, projecting its launch no earlier than early to mid May. After multiple successful test flights in the past few months, if the timeline holds true, SpaceX is poised to launch a manned mission into space before the deadline. Scheduling the launch for May allows SpaceX one month to finalize its plans and check for any other errors they might encounter along the way during the mission. I am more confident that the mission will occur now that there has been successful previous tests, and a concrete timeline that SpaceX can adhere to, than I was before.

This sunday, SpaceX will use the Falcon 9 to launch its sixth Starlink mission, and its first fifth booster flight. This is important because a successful fifth booster flight will increase the chances that reusable rockets will be used in the future more often. A successful test will increase the likelihood of a successful launch of a manned mission as the Falcon 9 will have another test under its belt, while also giving the SpaceX mission control more experience with launching critical and fragile equipment to low earth orbit. However, I believe that the Corunavirus outbreak will hinder progress as world markets stagnate, Musk may become more worried about issues on Earth rather than outside its atmosphere.

I'm hedging my bet now. I'm not sure how big the launch crew would have to be, but to guarantee a launch, the entire team will have to be quarantined for long enough to spot illness in them. To do that and do the launch, they will need to have redundancy in key positions and not just with the astronauts. So we would need to look for a quarantine to begin about five weeks before launch, which means we should see that happening in early April. Just 2 days ago on March 6, 2020 SpaceX successfully launched its Falcon 9 rocket on the company’s 20th cargo mission to the International Space Station, and had their 50th overall rocket landing for the company. This routine launch was significant because it is “the final resupply mission for NASA under SpaceX’s original contract with the space agency”. Now SpaceX will begin its work with the new Dragon 2 capsule which will be used to send people to the international space station. I suggest a 1% chance SpaceX will launch before July 1st this year, which is significantly lower than my previous prediction. Why? Axiom Space, “a company with ambitions to develop a private space station, announced March 5 that it has signed a contract with SpaceX for a commercial Crew Dragon mission to the International Space Station. Axiom said the mission, scheduled for launch no earlier than the second half of 2021, will carry one Axiom professional astronaut and three private astronauts to the ISS. The mission will last 10 days, including eight at the station and two in transit. The company did not disclose terms of the deal, nor pricing for the individual private astronauts. The flight announcement comes as Axiom works to raise outside investment. Suffredini said in that earlier interview that the company is in the process of raising a Series A funding round on the order of $100 million, which it hopes to close by the beginning of summer. The contract is the second deal for a commercial Crew Dragon mission announced in less than a month. Space Adventures announced Feb. 18 it had an agreement for a Crew Dragon mission launching between late 2021 and the middle of 2022. That flight, carrying four private astronauts, will not go to the ISS but instead fly in an orbit more than twice as high as the station. “Thanks to Axiom and their support from NASA, privately crewed missions will have unprecedented access to the space station, furthering the commercialization of space and helping usher in a new era of human exploration,” SpaceX President Gwynne Shotwell said in the Axiom statement”.

Based off of the available resources regarding SpaceX’s scheduled launch for this spring, I suggest there is a 78% chance that SpaceX will launch its first crewed mission into orbit before July 1, 2020. SpaceX Crew Dragon capsule arrived on Florida's Space Coast on Thursday (Feb. 13), and now Technicians can start prepping the vehicle for the launch that will kick off Demo-2, a test mission that will send NASA astronauts Doug Hurley and Bob Behnken to the International Space Station (ISS). SpaceX's Crew Dragon capsule aced an in-flight abort test Sunday morning (Jan. 19), successfully jetting away from its Falcon 9 rocket less than 90 seconds after liftoff and demonstrated the spacecraft's ability to keep astronauts safe in the event of a launch emergency, marking a big step on the path toward crewed flight. In terms of the astronauts capabilities, Behnken and Hurley have been working closely with SpaceX on the Crew Dragon's development since 2015, so they're well equipped to fly the spacecraft. In total, the two astronauts have worked together for two decades. As of 17 February 2020, Falcon 9 has achieved 82 out of 84 full mission successes (97.6%), so it is sound to say they have a dependable record regarding safety and mission performance.

My first estimate is therefore based on SpaceX's success rate. My only thought will be the non-launch related impact of Covid-19 on the launch facility staffing and space program. I would expect the crew and back up will be put into preventative isolation for up to six weeks before launch. If the launch facility is closed because of it, however, there will be no flight.
